{"title_page": "Nasir Ahmad el-Rufai", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Tone|date=September 2008}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Nasir Ahmad El-Rufai\n| image               = \n| office1             = [[Governor of Kaduna State]]\n| deputy1             = [[Yusuf Barnabas Bala]]<br>[[Hadiza Sabuwa Balarabe]]<ref>http://kdsg.gov.ng/deputy-governor/</ref>\n| predecessor1        = [[Mukhtar Ramalan Yero]]\n| successor1          = \n| term_start1         = 29 May 2015\n| term_end1           = \n| office2             = [[Minister of the Federal Capital Territory]]\n| president2          = [[Olusegun Obasanjo]]\n| term_start2         = 17 July 2003\n| term_end2           = 27 July 2007\n| predecessor2        = [[Mohammed Abba Gana]]\n| successor2          = [[Aliyu Modibbo Umar]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1960|2|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Daudawa]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]], [[British Nigeria]]<br>(now [[Daudawa]], Nigeria)\n| party               = [[All Progressives Congress|APC]] (from 2013)\n| spouse              = {{Collapsible list |title=''See''|1=[[Hadiza Isma El-Rufai]]<br/>Asia Ahmad<br/>Aisha Ummi Garba}}\n| alma_mater          = [[Ahmadu Bello University]]<br>[[Harvard University]]<br>[[Georgetown University]]<br>[[University of London]]\n| education           = [[Barewa College]]\n| otherparty          = [[Peoples Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]] (until 2009)<br>[[Congress for Progressive Change|CPC]] (2011\u20132013)\n}}\n                                             \n[[Mallam (title)|Mallam]] '''Nasir Ahmad El-Rufai''' (born 16 February 1960)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nigeriavillagesquare.com/articles/nasir-el-rufai.html |title=NVS Articles & Viewpoints \u2013 Nigerian Village Square |publisher=Nigeriavillagesquare.com |accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref> is a Nigerian politician who is the [[Governor of Kaduna State]] since 2015. He was previously the [[Minister of the Federal Capital Territory]] from 2003 to 2007; and the director of the [[Bureau of Public Enterprises]]. He is a founding member of the ruling [[All Progressives Congress]].\n\n==Family and personal life==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nNasir Ahmad El-Rufai was born on February 16, 1960 to a [[Fula people|Fulani]] family in [[Daudawa]]. His father died while he was 8 years old, and he was sponsored through his early schooling by an uncle in [[Kaduna]].<ref name=\"Profile: Mallam Nasir el-Rufai\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3634616.stm|title=Profile: Mallam Nasir el-Rufai|date=7 September 2004|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 May 2010}}</ref> El-Rufai was educated in [[Barewa College]]. As a junior at the college, [[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Umaru Musa Yar'Adua|Umaru Yar'Adua]] was the house captain of his dormitory.<ref>[http://www.nigeriafirst.org/docs/ministers_profiles.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060721044351/http://www.nigeriafirst.org/docs/ministers_profiles.htm|date=21 July 2006}}</ref> In 1976, he graduated at the top of his class, winning the \"Barewa Old Boys' Association Academic Achievement\" Trophy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bahaushe Mai Ban Haushi! |url=http://ibrahim-sheme.blogspot.com/2009/06/yaradua-great-expectation-disappointing.html |title=Bahaushe Mai Ban Haushi!: Yar\u2019Adua: Great Expectation, Disappointing Outcome |publisher=Ibrahim-sheme.blogspot.com |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe then proceeded to [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]], where he received a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[Quantity Surveying|quantity surveying]] with first class honours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linkedin.com/pub/nasir-el-rufai/11/369/b |title=Nasir El Rufai |publisher=LinkedIn |accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref> In 1984, he received a [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[Harvard Business School]]. El Rufai has attended several professional and post-graduate programs, including the [[Georgetown School of Foreign Service]] of [[Georgetown University]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amsterdamandpartners.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/White-Paper-Reform-vs-Status-Quo.pdf|title=White Paper: Reform vs Status|last=Amsterdam|first=Rober|date=December 1, 2009|website=Amsterdam & Partners|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n=== Family ===\nEl-Rufai is married to three wives, including writer and novelist [[Hadiza Isma El-Rufai]]. Together, they run the Yasmin El-Rufai Foundation (YELF), set up in honour of his daughter who died in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://punchng.com/i-used-to-sing-in-the-catholic-church-choir-hadiza-el-rufai/|title=I used to sing in the Catholic Church choir \u2014 Hadiza El-Rufai|work=Punch Newspapers|access-date=2018-01-07|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nEl-Rufai tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on March 28 2020, following contact with an index case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-el-rufai-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/|title=UPDATED: El-Rufai tests positive for coronavirus|last=Published|website=Punch Newspapers|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> He has placed a curfew in Kaduna State and restricted movement, to prevent the spread of the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/el-rufai-announces-partial-lockdown-in-kaduna/|title=El-Rufai announces partial lockdown in Kaduna|date=2020-03-24|website=Latest Nigeria News, Nigerian Newspapers, Politics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 1982, he founded El-Rufai & Partners, a quantity surveying consulting firm with three partners which he managed until 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://erp-dca.com/sustainability/about/|title=El Rufai and Partners: Design Cost Associates|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> During the [[Nigerian military juntas of 1966\u201379 and 1983\u201398|military junta's of 1983\u20131998]], the firm received building and civil engineering contracts including during the construction of [[Abuja]], making the partners \"young millionaires\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3634616.stm|title=Profile: Mallam Nasir el-Rufai|date=2004-09-07|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nIn addition to his practice, El-Rufai held management positions with two international telecommunications companies, [[AT&T]] Network Systems International BV and [[Motorola, Inc]]. He also attended several professional programs on privatisation and leadership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amsterdamandpartners.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/White-Paper-Reform-vs-Status-Quo.pdf|title=White Paper: Reform vs Status|last=Amsterdam|first=Rober|date=December 1, 2009|website=Amsterdam & Partners|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Political career ==\nIn 1998, following the death of military dictator [[Sani Abacha]], his successor [[Abdulsalami Abubakar]] appointed El-Rufai as an economic advisor. In this role he worked with the [[World Bank]] and [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amsterdamandpartners.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/White-Paper-Reform-vs-Status-Quo.pdf|title=White Paper: Reform vs Status|last=Amsterdam|first=Rober|date=December 1, 2009|website=Amsterdam & Partners|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following the [[1999 Nigerian presidential election|1999 presidential election]], the military transferred power to President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] giving rise to the [[Fourth Nigerian Republic]].\n\n=== Privatisation czar ===\nIn November 1999, he was appointed the director of the [[Bureau of Public Enterprises]], and secretary of the [[National Council on Privatisation|National Council of Privatisation]] where he spearheaded the privatisation of several government owned corporations alongside Vice President [[Atiku Abubakar]].<ref>http://en.newspeg.com/Nigeria-El-Rufai-Has-Zero-Tolerance-for-Corruption---Obj-3926799.html{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Minister of the Federal Capital Territory ===\nIn July 2003, he was appointed the [[Minister of the Federal Capital Territory]]. During his tenure, he presided over a radical transformation of the federal capital earlier riddled with corruption and vast deviation from the original masterplan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6355269.stm|title=Life of poverty in Abuja's wealth|date=2007-02-13|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> With the establishment of the Abuja Geographic Information System, the capital became the first municipality in Nigeria with a computerised land register and information system.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peter-Omale|first=Funmi|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200604110206.html|title=Nigeria: Abuja Land Registry Nets N4bn in 2005 - El Rufai|date=2006-04-11|work=This Day (Lagos)|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> \n\nAlong with the President and members of the Economic Management Team, he led the reform of the Nigerian public service which had become dysfunctional during years of military dictatorship.<ref>[http://www.sunnewsonline.com/webpages/features/powergame/2009/feb/08/powergame-08-02-2009-004.htm] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417054150/http://www.sunnewsonline.com/webpages/features/powergame/2009/feb/08/powergame-08-02-2009-004.htm |date=17 April 2009 }}</ref> At various times during his tenure as Minister, he oversaw the Federal Ministries of Commerce (twice) and Interior.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200804160123.html|title=Nigeria: Is El-Rufai Really Guilty?|last=Oota|first=Andrew|date=2008-04-16|work=Leadership (Abuja)|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> He also chaired several high-profile cabinet committees that led to the establishment of a mortgage system in Nigeria,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independentngonline.com/DailyIndependent/Article.aspx?id=3075|title=independentngonline.com|website=www.independentngonline.com|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> National ID card system for Nigeria,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nigerianmuse.com/20091017150021zg/nigeriawatch/mallam-nasir-el-rufai-s-interview-this-day-october-17-2009 |title=Mallam Nasir el-Rufai &#124; NigerianMuse |publisher=Nigerianmuse.com |accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref> Electric Power Supply Improvement and the sale of Federal Government real estate in Abuja.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200804110005.html|title=Nigeria: 75,000 Houses Demolished in Abuja Under El-Rufai|last=Ojeifo|first=Sufuyan|date=2008-04-11|work=This Day (Lagos)|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>\n\nDuring the last days of the Obasanjo administration, [[Nuhu Ribadu]], a one-time El-Rufai ally described him as the \"de facto No. 2 official\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punchontheweb.com/Article2Print.aspx?theartic=Art200910170442631|title=The Punch :: How Obasanjo granted el-Rufai the power to rule Abuja without the FCT ministry \u2013 Dr. Layi Ogunbambi|author=Vincent Akanmode|publisher=Punchontheweb.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20111002094126/http://www.punchontheweb.com/Article2Print.aspx?theartic=Art200910170442631|archivedate=2 October 2011|accessdate=18 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> tagging him with the role of Vice President, especially after the fall-out between Obasanjo and his vice president Atiku Abubakar. It is believed that Obasanjo's trust and confidence in El-Rufai angered a vast majority of the political class, which would later persecute him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elombah.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1664:civil-service-reform-yayale-loses-out-in-power-game&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=67|title=Civil Service Reform: Yayale loses out in Power game|date=20 September 2009|publisher=Elombah.com|accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Exile and return ===\nIn 2008, following [[Umaru Musa Yar'Adua|Umaru Yar'Adua]] rise to power, El-Rufai went into self-imposed exile and became a vocal critic of the adminsitration. In exile, he received a [[Bachelor of Laws|law degree]] from the [[University of London]] in August 2008, and a [[master's degree]] in [[public administration]] from the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] of [[Harvard University]] in June 2009. He also received the Kennedy School Certificate in Public Policy and Management having spent 11 months as an Edward A. Mason Fellow in Public Policy and Management from July 2008 to June 2009.<ref>[http://www.whartonafricaforum.com/2008/speakers.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109224644/http://www.whartonafricaforum.com/2008/speakers.html|date=9 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he returned to Nigeria and was subsequently arrested by the [[Economic and Financial Crimes Commission]]. He explained his return was in order to clear his name of corruption charges.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Camillus Eboh|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/idAFJOE6440CF20100505|title=Nigerian reformer bailed after return from exile|work=AF|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en-US}}</ref> El-Rufai later joined party politics with the [[Congress for Progressive Change|Congres for Progressive Change]] supporting [[Muhammadu Buhari]]'s campaign in the [[2011 Nigerian presidential election|2011 presidential election]]. In 2013, El-Rufai was appointed deputy national secretary of the newly formed [[All Progressives Congress]] (APC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/139592-masari-el-rufai-others-emerge-apc-interim-national-officers.html|title=Masari, El-Rufai, others emerge APC interim national officers - Premium Times Nigeria|last=Owete|first=Festus|date=2013-06-25|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Kaduna==\nIn 2014, following the APC governorship primaries El-Rufai emerged as the party's candidate for [[Governor of Kaduna State]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/more-news/172496-el-rufai-declared-kaduna-apc-governorship-candidate.html|title=El-rufai declared Kaduna APC governorship candidate - Premium Times Nigeria|date=2014-12-05|work=Premium Times Nigeria|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-GB}}</ref> He went on to win the governorship election, securing over 1.1 million votes to defeat the incumbent Governor [[Mukhtar Ramalan Yero]] the candidate of the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gongnews.net/el-rufai-polled-1117635-to-defeat-incumbent-yero-with-485833-votes/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020180609/http://www.gongnews.net/el-rufai-polled-1117635-to-defeat-incumbent-yero-with-485833-votes/ |archivedate=20 October 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The election was upheld by the election petition tribunal in October 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/more-news/191568-tribunal-upholds-governor-el-rufais-election.html|title=Tribunal upholds Governor El-Rufai's election - Premium Times Nigeria|date=2015-10-15|work=Premium Times Nigeria|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2015, El-Rufai was sworn in as the 22nd Governor of Kaduna State.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://leadership.ng/news/437086/leadership-by-example-el-rufai-deputy-cut-own-salaries-by-50 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021000728/http://leadership.ng/news/437086/leadership-by-example-el-rufai-deputy-cut-own-salaries-by-50 |archivedate=21 October 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In his inaugural address, he declared that he and his deputy were cutting their allowances by half pending an improvement in the state's fiscal situation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2015/05/swearing-in-el-rufai-deputy-cut-own-salaries-by-50/|title=Democracy Day: El Rufai, deputy, cut own salaries by 50%   - Vanguard News|date=2015-05-29|work=Vanguard News|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US}}</ref> On 6 August 2015, El-Rufai in one of his first acts as governor announced that Kaduna State will adopt the Treasury Single Account policy by 1 September of the same year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nigerianwatch.com/news/7525-governor-el-rufai-orders-closure-of-all-kaduna-states-commercial-bank-accounts |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020181029/http://www.nigerianwatch.com/news/7525-governor-el-rufai-orders-closure-of-all-kaduna-states-commercial-bank-accounts |archivedate=20 October 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> At the end of the exercise, 470 accounts belonging to different ministries, departments and agencies were closed and a sum of N24.7 billion was recovered and remitted to the Kaduna State Government TSA with the Central Bank of Nigeria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kdsg.gov.ng/tsa-is-an-armor-against-waste-and-leakage/|title=TSA is an armor against waste and leakage \u2013 Kaduna State Government|website=kdsg.gov.ng|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>\n\nEl-Rufai also reformed the civil service in Kaduna State and reduced the number of ministries from 19 to 13 and the number of permanent secretaries from 35 to 18.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201508060625.html|title=Nigeria: X-Raying El - Rufai's 60 Days in Office|last=John|first=Gabriel|date=2015-08-06|work=Daily Independent (Lagos)|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> In a bid to reduce the cost of governance, El-Rufai appointed only 13 commissioners, 10 special advisers and 12 special assistants as against the 24 commissioners, 41 special advisers and about 400 special assistants appointed by the previous administration.<ref>http://ynaija.com/nasir-el-rufai-achieved-kaduna-state-governor-one-month/</ref> By blocking leakages and cutting the cost of running government, it is estimated that the El-Rufai administration was able to save N1.2 billion in just two months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thenationonlineng.net/el-rufai-saved-n1-2-billion-in-two-months-sani/|title=El-Rufai saved N1.2 billion in two months -Sani - The Nation Nigeria|date=2015-09-06|work=The Nation Nigeria|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, El-Rufai's administration launched the School Feeding Programme, aimed at providing one free meal per day to 1.5 million pupils in public primary schools within the state.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.naij.com/699901-photos-governor-el-rufai-launches-school-feeding-programme-kaduna.html|title=GOOD NEWS: El-Rufai Launches Free School Feeding Program In Kaduna (Photos)|last=Nwodo|first=Anike|date=2016-01-18|work=Naija.ng - Nigeria news.|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US}}</ref> His administration also abolished the collection of fees and levies in public primary and junior secondary schools in Kaduna, thereby removing a financial burden of N3 billion from the parents. \n\nOn the March 9, 2019, El-Rufai was re-elected defeating the PDP opposition by over 200,000 votes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Breaking: INEC declares El-Rufai winner of Kaduna governorship election |url=https://oak.tv/newstrack/el-rufai-retains-kaduna-governorship-election/ |accessdate=13 March 2019 |work=Oak TV Newstrack |publisher=oak tv |date=11 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930163800/http://www.thisdayonline.com/nview.php?id=25798 ''This Day'' (Lagos) on el-Rufai, 20 August 2005]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3634616.stm ''BBC'' on Nasir el-Rufai, 7 September 2004,]\n*[http://www.nigeriatop.com/ ''Nigeria Top Politics,'' /Facts on our politicians]\n\n{{AbujaFCTMinisters}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rufai, Nasir Ahmad el-}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Ministers of the Federal Capital Territory (Nigeria)]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government staff]]\n[[Category:Ahmadu Bello University alumni]]\n[[Category:People's Democratic Party (Nigeria) politicians]]\n[[Category:Federal ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:All Progressives Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Barewa College alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of Kaduna State]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n \n[[Category:Politicians from Kaduna State]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2015 Nigerian general election]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Tone|date=September 2008}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Nasir Ahmad El-Rufai\n| image               = \n| office1             = [[Governor of Kaduna State]]\n| deputy1             = [[Yusuf Barnabas Bala]]<br>[[Hadiza Sabuwa Balarabe]]<ref>http://kdsg.gov.ng/deputy-governor/</ref>\n| predecessor1        = [[Mukhtar Ramalan Yero]]\n| successor1          = \n| term_start1         = 29 May 2015\n| term_end1           = \n| office2             = [[Minister of the Federal Capital Territory]]\n| president2          = [[Olusegun Obasanjo]]\n| term_start2         = 17 July 2003\n| term_end2           = 27 July 2007\n| predecessor2        = [[Mohammed Abba Gana]]\n| successor2          = [[Aliyu Modibbo Umar]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1960|2|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Daudawa]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]], [[British Nigeria]]<br>(now [[Daudawa]], Nigeria)\n| party               = [[All Progressives Congress|APC]] (from 2013)\n| spouse              = {{Collapsible list |title=''See''|1=[[Hadiza Isma El-Rufai]]<br/>Asia Ahmad<br/>Aisha Ummi Garba}}\n| alma_mater          = [[Ahmadu Bello University]]<br>[[Harvard University]]<br>[[Georgetown University]]<br>[[University of London]]\n| education           = [[Barewa College]]\n| otherparty          = [[Peoples Democratic Party (Nigeria)|PDP]] (until 2009)<br>[[Congress for Progressive Change|CPC]] (2011\u20132013)\n}}\n                                             \n[[Mallam (title)|Mallam]] '''Nasir Ahmad El-Rufai''' (born 16 February 1960)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nigeriavillagesquare.com/articles/nasir-el-rufai.html |title=NVS Articles & Viewpoints \u2013 Nigerian Village Square |publisher=Nigeriavillagesquare.com |accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref> is a Nigerian politician who is the [[Governor of Kaduna State]] since 2015. He was previously the [[Minister of the Federal Capital Territory]] from 2003 to 2007; and the director of the [[Bureau of Public Enterprises]]. He is a founding member of the ruling [[All Progressives Congress]].\n\n==Family and personal life==\n\n=== Early life ===\nNasir Ahmad El-Rufai was born on February 16, 1960 to a [[Fula people|Fulani]] family in [[Daudawa]]. His father died while he was 8 years old, and he was sponsored through his early schooling by an uncle in [[Kaduna]].<ref name=\"Profile: Mallam Nasir el-Rufai\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3634616.stm|title=Profile: Mallam Nasir el-Rufai|date=7 September 2004|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nEl-Rufai was educated in [[Barewa College]]. As a junior at the college, [[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Umaru Musa Yar'Adua|Umaru Yar'Adua]] was the house captain of his dormitory.<ref>[http://www.nigeriafirst.org/docs/ministers_profiles.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060721044351/http://www.nigeriafirst.org/docs/ministers_profiles.htm|date=21 July 2006}}</ref> In 1976, he graduated at the top of his class, winning the \"Barewa Old Boys' Association Academic Achievement\" Trophy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bahaushe Mai Ban Haushi! |url=http://ibrahim-sheme.blogspot.com/2009/06/yaradua-great-expectation-disappointing.html |title=Bahaushe Mai Ban Haushi!: Yar\u2019Adua: Great Expectation, Disappointing Outcome |publisher=Ibrahim-sheme.blogspot.com |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref> \n\nHe then proceeded to [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]], where he received a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[Quantity Surveying|quantity surveying]] with first class honours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linkedin.com/pub/nasir-el-rufai/11/369/b |title=Nasir El Rufai |publisher=LinkedIn |accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref> In 1984, he received a [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[Harvard Business School]]. \n\nEl Rufai has attended several professional and post-graduate programs, including the [[Georgetown School of Foreign Service]] of [[Georgetown University]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amsterdamandpartners.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/White-Paper-Reform-vs-Status-Quo.pdf|title=White Paper: Reform vs Status|last=Amsterdam|first=Rober|date=December 1, 2009|website=Amsterdam & Partners|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n=== Family ===\nEl-Rufai is married to three wives, including writer and novelist [[Hadiza Isma El-Rufai]]. Together, they run the Yasmin El-Rufai Foundation (YELF), set up in honour of his daughter who died in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://punchng.com/i-used-to-sing-in-the-catholic-church-choir-hadiza-el-rufai/|title=I used to sing in the Catholic Church choir \u2014 Hadiza El-Rufai|work=Punch Newspapers|access-date=2018-01-07|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 1982, he founded El-Rufai & Partners, a quantity surveying consulting firm with three partners which he managed until 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://erp-dca.com/sustainability/about/|title=El Rufai and Partners: Design Cost Associates|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> During the [[Nigerian military juntas of 1966\u201379 and 1983\u201398|military junta's of 1983\u20131998]], the firm received building and civil engineering contracts including during the construction of [[Abuja]], making the partners \"young millionaires\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3634616.stm|title=Profile: Mallam Nasir el-Rufai|date=2004-09-07|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nIn addition to his practice, El-Rufai held management positions with two international telecommunications companies, [[AT&T]] Network Systems International BV and [[Motorola, Inc]]. He also attended several professional programs on privatisation and leadership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amsterdamandpartners.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/White-Paper-Reform-vs-Status-Quo.pdf|title=White Paper: Reform vs Status|last=Amsterdam|first=Rober|date=December 1, 2009|website=Amsterdam & Partners|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Political career ==\nIn 1998, following the death of military dictator [[Sani Abacha]], his successor [[Abdulsalami Abubakar]] appointed El-Rufai as an economic advisor. In this role he worked with the [[World Bank]] and [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amsterdamandpartners.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/White-Paper-Reform-vs-Status-Quo.pdf|title=White Paper: Reform vs Status|last=Amsterdam|first=Rober|date=December 1, 2009|website=Amsterdam & Partners|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following the [[1999 Nigerian presidential election|1999 presidential election]], the military transferred power to President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] giving rise to the [[Fourth Nigerian Republic]].\n\n=== Privatisation czar ===\nIn November 1999, he was appointed the director of the [[Bureau of Public Enterprises]], and secretary of the [[National Council on Privatisation|National Council of Privatisation]] where he spearheaded the privatisation of several government owned corporations alongside Vice President [[Atiku Abubakar]].<ref>http://en.newspeg.com/Nigeria-El-Rufai-Has-Zero-Tolerance-for-Corruption---Obj-3926799.html{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Minister of the Federal Capital Territory ===\nIn July 2003, he was appointed the [[Minister of the Federal Capital Territory]]. During his tenure, he presided over a radical transformation of the federal capital earlier riddled with corruption and vast deviation from the original masterplan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6355269.stm|title=Life of poverty in Abuja's wealth|date=2007-02-13|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> With the establishment of the Abuja Geographic Information System, the capital became the first municipality in Nigeria with a computerised land register and information system.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peter-Omale|first=Funmi|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200604110206.html|title=Nigeria: Abuja Land Registry Nets N4bn in 2005 - El Rufai|date=2006-04-11|work=This Day (Lagos)|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> \n\nAlong with the President and members of the Economic Management Team, he led the reform of the Nigerian public service which had become dysfunctional during years of military dictatorship.<ref>[http://www.sunnewsonline.com/webpages/features/powergame/2009/feb/08/powergame-08-02-2009-004.htm] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417054150/http://www.sunnewsonline.com/webpages/features/powergame/2009/feb/08/powergame-08-02-2009-004.htm |date=17 April 2009 }}</ref> At various times during his tenure as Minister, he oversaw the Federal Ministries of Commerce (twice) and Interior.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200804160123.html|title=Nigeria: Is El-Rufai Really Guilty?|last=Oota|first=Andrew|date=2008-04-16|work=Leadership (Abuja)|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> He also chaired several high-profile cabinet committees that led to the establishment of a mortgage system in Nigeria,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independentngonline.com/DailyIndependent/Article.aspx?id=3075|title=independentngonline.com|website=www.independentngonline.com|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> National ID card system for Nigeria,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nigerianmuse.com/20091017150021zg/nigeriawatch/mallam-nasir-el-rufai-s-interview-this-day-october-17-2009 |title=Mallam Nasir el-Rufai &#124; NigerianMuse |publisher=Nigerianmuse.com |accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref> Electric Power Supply Improvement and the sale of Federal Government real estate in Abuja.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200804110005.html|title=Nigeria: 75,000 Houses Demolished in Abuja Under El-Rufai|last=Ojeifo|first=Sufuyan|date=2008-04-11|work=This Day (Lagos)|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>\n\nDuring the last days of the Obasanjo administration, [[Nuhu Ribadu]], a one-time El-Rufai ally described him as the \"de facto No. 2 official\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punchontheweb.com/Article2Print.aspx?theartic=Art200910170442631|title=The Punch :: How Obasanjo granted el-Rufai the power to rule Abuja without the FCT ministry \u2013 Dr. Layi Ogunbambi|author=Vincent Akanmode|publisher=Punchontheweb.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20111002094126/http://www.punchontheweb.com/Article2Print.aspx?theartic=Art200910170442631|archivedate=2 October 2011|accessdate=18 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> tagging him with the role of Vice President, especially after the fall-out between Obasanjo and his vice president Atiku Abubakar. It is believed that Obasanjo's trust and confidence in El-Rufai angered a vast majority of the political class, which would later persecute him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elombah.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1664:civil-service-reform-yayale-loses-out-in-power-game&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=67|title=Civil Service Reform: Yayale loses out in Power game|date=20 September 2009|publisher=Elombah.com|accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Exile and return ===\nIn 2008, following [[Umaru Musa Yar'Adua|Umaru Yar'Adua]] rise to power, El-Rufai went into self-imposed exile and became a vocal critic of the adminsitration. In exile, he received a [[Bachelor of Laws|law degree]] from the [[University of London]] in August 2008, and a [[master's degree]] in [[public administration]] from the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] of [[Harvard University]] in June 2009. He also received the Kennedy School Certificate in Public Policy and Management having spent 11 months as an Edward A. Mason Fellow in Public Policy and Management from July 2008 to June 2009.<ref>[http://www.whartonafricaforum.com/2008/speakers.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109224644/http://www.whartonafricaforum.com/2008/speakers.html|date=9 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he returned to Nigeria and was subsequently arrested by the [[Economic and Financial Crimes Commission]]. He explained his return was in order to clear his name of corruption charges.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Camillus Eboh|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/idAFJOE6440CF20100505|title=Nigerian reformer bailed after return from exile|work=AF|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en-US}}</ref> El-Rufai later joined party politics with the [[Congress for Progressive Change|Congres for Progressive Change]] supporting [[Muhammadu Buhari]]'s campaign in the [[2011 Nigerian presidential election|2011 presidential election]]. In 2013, El-Rufai was appointed deputy national secretary of the newly formed [[All Progressives Congress]] (APC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/139592-masari-el-rufai-others-emerge-apc-interim-national-officers.html|title=Masari, El-Rufai, others emerge APC interim national officers - Premium Times Nigeria|last=Owete|first=Festus|date=2013-06-25|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Kaduna==\nIn 2014, following the APC governorship primaries El-Rufai emerged as the party's candidate for [[Governor of Kaduna State]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/more-news/172496-el-rufai-declared-kaduna-apc-governorship-candidate.html|title=El-rufai declared Kaduna APC governorship candidate - Premium Times Nigeria|date=2014-12-05|work=Premium Times Nigeria|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-GB}}</ref> He went on to win the governorship election, securing over 1.1 million votes to defeat the incumbent Governor [[Mukhtar Ramalan Yero]] the candidate of the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gongnews.net/el-rufai-polled-1117635-to-defeat-incumbent-yero-with-485833-votes/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020180609/http://www.gongnews.net/el-rufai-polled-1117635-to-defeat-incumbent-yero-with-485833-votes/ |archivedate=20 October 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The election was upheld by the election petition tribunal in October 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/more-news/191568-tribunal-upholds-governor-el-rufais-election.html|title=Tribunal upholds Governor El-Rufai's election - Premium Times Nigeria|date=2015-10-15|work=Premium Times Nigeria|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2015, El-Rufai was sworn in as the 22nd Governor of Kaduna State.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://leadership.ng/news/437086/leadership-by-example-el-rufai-deputy-cut-own-salaries-by-50 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021000728/http://leadership.ng/news/437086/leadership-by-example-el-rufai-deputy-cut-own-salaries-by-50 |archivedate=21 October 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In his inaugural address, he declared that he and his deputy were cutting their allowances by half pending an improvement in the state's fiscal situation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2015/05/swearing-in-el-rufai-deputy-cut-own-salaries-by-50/|title=Democracy Day: El Rufai, deputy, cut own salaries by 50%   - Vanguard News|date=2015-05-29|work=Vanguard News|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US}}</ref> On 6 August 2015, El-Rufai in one of his first acts as governor announced that Kaduna State will adopt the Treasury Single Account policy by 1 September of the same year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nigerianwatch.com/news/7525-governor-el-rufai-orders-closure-of-all-kaduna-states-commercial-bank-accounts |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-10-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020181029/http://www.nigerianwatch.com/news/7525-governor-el-rufai-orders-closure-of-all-kaduna-states-commercial-bank-accounts |archivedate=20 October 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> At the end of the exercise, 470 accounts belonging to different ministries, departments and agencies were closed and a sum of N24.7 billion was recovered and remitted to the Kaduna State Government TSA with the Central Bank of Nigeria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kdsg.gov.ng/tsa-is-an-armor-against-waste-and-leakage/|title=TSA is an armor against waste and leakage \u2013 Kaduna State Government|website=kdsg.gov.ng|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>\n\nEl-Rufai also reformed the civil service in Kaduna State and reduced the number of ministries from 19 to 13 and the number of permanent secretaries from 35 to 18.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201508060625.html|title=Nigeria: X-Raying El - Rufai's 60 Days in Office|last=John|first=Gabriel|date=2015-08-06|work=Daily Independent (Lagos)|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> In a bid to reduce the cost of governance, El-Rufai appointed only 13 commissioners, 10 special advisers and 12 special assistants as against the 24 commissioners, 41 special advisers and about 400 special assistants appointed by the previous administration.<ref>http://ynaija.com/nasir-el-rufai-achieved-kaduna-state-governor-one-month/</ref> By blocking leakages and cutting the cost of running government, it is estimated that the El-Rufai administration was able to save N1.2 billion in just two months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thenationonlineng.net/el-rufai-saved-n1-2-billion-in-two-months-sani/|title=El-Rufai saved N1.2 billion in two months -Sani - The Nation Nigeria|date=2015-09-06|work=The Nation Nigeria|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, El-Rufai's administration launched the School Feeding Programme, aimed at providing one free meal per day to 1.5 million pupils in public primary schools within the state.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.naij.com/699901-photos-governor-el-rufai-launches-school-feeding-programme-kaduna.html|title=GOOD NEWS: El-Rufai Launches Free School Feeding Program In Kaduna (Photos)|last=Nwodo|first=Anike|date=2016-01-18|work=Naija.ng - Nigeria news.|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US}}</ref> His administration also abolished the collection of fees and levies in public primary and junior secondary schools in Kaduna, thereby removing a financial burden of N3 billion from the parents. \n\nOn the March 9, 2019, El-Rufai was re-elected defeating the PDP opposition by over 200,000 votes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Breaking: INEC declares El-Rufai winner of Kaduna governorship election |url=https://oak.tv/newstrack/el-rufai-retains-kaduna-governorship-election/ |accessdate=13 March 2019 |work=Oak TV Newstrack |publisher=oak tv |date=11 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930163800/http://www.thisdayonline.com/nview.php?id=25798 ''This Day'' (Lagos) on el-Rufai, 20 August 2005]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3634616.stm ''BBC'' on Nasir el-Rufai, 7 September 2004,]\n*[http://www.nigeriatop.com/ ''Nigeria Top Politics,'' /Facts on our politicians]\n\n{{AbujaFCTMinisters}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rufai, Nasir Ahmad el-}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Ministers of the Federal Capital Territory (Nigeria)]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government staff]]\n[[Category:Ahmadu Bello University alumni]]\n[[Category:People's Democratic Party (Nigeria) politicians]]\n[[Category:Federal ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:All Progressives Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Barewa College alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of Kaduna State]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n \n[[Category:Politicians from Kaduna State]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2015 Nigerian general election]]\n", "name_user": "Zerzuran", "label": "safe", "comment": "Health update; and referencing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nasir_Ahmad_el-Rufai"}
{"title_page": "Harish Patel", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Harish Patel\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = Harish Patel in 2009\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1953|7|df=y|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|df=yes|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Indian\n| other_names = \n| years_active = 1983&ndash;present\n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = Actor\n}}\n'''Harish Patel''' (born 5 July 1953 in [[Mumbai]], [[India]]) is an Indian actor. Although mainly associated with the stage, he has appeared in films and on television.\n\n==Biography==\nPatel was born in Mumbai, India. He began performing at the age of seven, when he played male and female parts in the [[Hindu]] epic ''[[Ramayana]]''. He made his film debut in ''[[Mandi (film)|Mandi]]'' directed by [[Shyam Benegal]] in 1983.\n\nFrom 1994 to 2008, Patel worked with the eminent Indian theatre director [[Satyadev Dubey]]. In 1995, he joined the [[Indian National Theatre]] and appeared in the play ''[[Neela Kamra]]''. His repertoire has included classical and modern Indian plays as well as plays by Western writers, e.g., [[Pinter]]'s ''[[The Caretaker]]'', [[Sartre]]'s ''[[No Exit]]'', [[Albert Camus|Camus]]' ''[[Cross Purpose]]'', [[Ionesco]]'s ''[[The Lesson]]'', and [[Mrozek]]'s ''[[Vatzlav]]''.\n\nIn the spring of 2007, Patel took the lead role of Eeshwar Dutt in ''[[Rafta, Rafta...]]'', a comedy written by [[Ayub Khan-Din]] and directed by [[Nicholas Hytner]] at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] in [[London]] to critical acclaim and sellout audiences.<ref>{{cite web|title=LAURENCE OLIVIER WINNERS\u2019 REMARKS: Best New Play & Best New Comedy|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/03-2008/speeches-and-the-laurence-olivier-winners-said_19804.html|website=What's On Stage}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rafta Rafta \u2013 Royal National Theatre|url=http://www.japjitkaur.com/projects/rafta-rafta-royal-national-theatre/|website=Japjit Kaur}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Patel|first1=Chandrika|title=The Taste of British South Asian Theatres: Aesthetics and Production|date=2015|publisher=Lulu Press|isbn=9781483433417|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EBafCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT103&lpg=PT103&dq=harish+patel+%2B+theatre&source=bl&ots=5zIsLsmuXA&sig=GYm51BVnINQnZhN2ect9skhcujQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzg6PR5t7KAhVKnRoKHdmRAlsQ6AEIUzAI#v=onepage&q=harish%20patel%20%2B%20theatre&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"The Guardian 1 May 2007\">{{cite web|title=Wanted: multicultural audiences for mainstream theatre|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/theatreblog/2007/may/01/wantedmulticulturalaudiences|website=The Guardian|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nHis credits include ''[[The Buddha of Suburbia (TV serial)|The Buddha of Suburbia]]'', ''[[China Gate (1998 film)|China Gate]]'', ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr India]]'' and ''[[Run Fatboy Run]]''.<ref name=\"The Asian Today 5 Sep 2007\">{{cite web|title=\u2018I couldn\u2019t say no to David\u2019 \u2013 Harish Patel|url=http://www.theasiantoday.com/index.php/2007/09/05/i-couldnt-say-no-to-david-harish-patel/|publisher=The Asian Today}}</ref> In 2009 he appeared in ''[[Coronation Street]]'' playing the role of Umed, [[Dev Alahan]]'s uncle. Patel also appeared in ''[[Mr Stink (film)|Mr Stink]]'', ''[[Gangsta Granny (film)|Gangsta Granny]]'', ''[[The Boy in the Dress (film)|The Boy in the Dress]]'' and ''[[Billionaire Boy (film)|Billionaire Boy]]'', the television film adaptations of children's books by [[David Walliams]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Billionaire Boy|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/dw488j/billionaire-boy|website=Radio Times|publisher=Radio Times}}</ref> He plays shopkeeper Raj in all the films, although they are set in different places.\n\nHis acting career has taken him all over India, and he has performed in the United Kingdom and abroad, in the United States and [[Dubai]] among other countries. Patel is a life member of the [[Federation of Western India Cine Employees|Cine & TV Artists Association of India]].\n\nHe is well known for his catchphrase: ''gayee bhains paanee mein'' (the buffalo entered the water), in the movie, ''Mr. India''.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n\n===Television===\n* ''[[Four Weddings and a Funeral (miniseries)|Four Weddings and a Funeral]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Billionaire Boy (film)|Billionaire Boy]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Driver (TV series)|The Driver]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[The Boy in the Dress (film)|The Boy in the Dress]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Mapp and Lucia (BBC TV series)|Mapp and Lucia]]'' (2014)\n*\n\n* ''[[Gangsta Granny (film)|Gangsta Granny]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Mr Stink (film)|Mr Stink]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Baa Bahoo Aur Baby]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Coronation Street]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[The No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency (TV series)|The No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency]]'' (2008)\n* ''Gopaljee'' (1996)\n* ''[[The Buddha of Suburbia (TV serial)|The Buddha of Suburbia]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Wagle Ki Duniya]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Malgudi Days (TV series)|Malgudi Days]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Yatra (1986 TV series)|Yatra]]'' (1986)\n\n===Films===\n* ''Lies We Tell'' (2016)\n* ''[[Jadoo (UK film)|Jadoo]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Keith Lemon: The Film]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[All in Good Time (film)|All in Good Time]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Today's Special (film)|Today's Special]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Kisse Pyaar Karoon]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Run Fatboy Run]]'' (2007)\n* ''Chicken Tikka Masala'' (2005)\n* ''[[Pyaar Mein Twist]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Thoda Tum Badlo Thoda Hum]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Calcutta Mail]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Love at Times Square]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Ek Hindustani]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Kuch Tum Kaho Kuch Hum Kahein]]'' (2002)\n* ''Bokshu, the Myth'' (2002)<ref>{{cite web|last=Young|first=Deborah|title=Bokshu, The Myth|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/markets-festivals/bokshu-the-myth-1200515561/|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=18 December 2017|date=13 June 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Warrier|first=Shobha|title=Why can't an Indian make a film in English?|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2002/may/22sen.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=18 December 2017|date=22 May 2002}}</ref>\n* ''[[Pyaar Ishq Aur Mohabbat]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Zubeidaa]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Dhaai Akshar Prem Ke]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Krodh (film)|Krodh]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Jab Pyaar Kisise Hota Hai]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Gunda (1998 film)|Gunda]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Purani Kabar]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Gupt: The Hidden Truth]]''(1997)\n* ''[[Loha (1997 film)|Loha]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[My Son the Fanatic (film)|My Son the Fanatic]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Kama Sutra: A Tale of Love]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Ghatak: Lethal]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Mohra]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Andaz Apna Apna]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Aankhen (1993 film)|Aankhen]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Police Public]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Maine Pyaar Kiya]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr India]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Mandi (film)|Mandi]]'' (1983)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0665370}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patel, Harish}}\n[[Category:Male film actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Male television actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:British people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n\n\n{{theat-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Harish Patel\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = Harish Patel in 2009\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1953|7|df=y|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|df=yes|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Indian\n| other_names = \n| years_active = 1983&ndash;present\n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = Actor\n}}\n'''Harish Patel''' (born 5 July 1953 in [[Mumbai]], [[India]]) is an Indian actor. Although mainly associated with the stage, he has appeared in films and on television.\n\n==Biography==\nPatel was born in Mumbai, India. He is of Indian descent.<ref name=\"Actor Harish Patel on the show\">{{cite web|title=Actor Harish Patel on the show|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01fp30l|publisher=BBC|accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref> He began performing at the age of seven, when he played male and female parts in the [[Hindu]] epic ''[[Ramayana]]''. He made his film debut in ''[[Mandi (film)|Mandi]]'' directed by [[Shyam Benegal]] in 1983.\n\nFrom 1994 to 2008, Patel worked with the eminent Indian theatre director [[Satyadev Dubey]]. In 1995, he joined the [[Indian National Theatre]] and appeared in the play ''[[Neela Kamra]]''. His repertoire has included classical and modern Indian plays as well as plays by Western writers, e.g., [[Pinter]]'s ''[[The Caretaker]]'', [[Sartre]]'s ''[[No Exit]]'', [[Albert Camus|Camus]]' ''[[Cross Purpose]]'', [[Ionesco]]'s ''[[The Lesson]]'', and [[Mrozek]]'s ''[[Vatzlav]]''.\n\nIn the spring of 2007, Patel took the lead role of Eeshwar Dutt in ''[[Rafta, Rafta...]]'', a comedy written by [[Ayub Khan-Din]] and directed by [[Nicholas Hytner]] at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] in [[London]] to critical acclaim and sellout audiences.<ref>{{cite web|title=LAURENCE OLIVIER WINNERS\u2019 REMARKS: Best New Play & Best New Comedy|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/03-2008/speeches-and-the-laurence-olivier-winners-said_19804.html|website=What's On Stage}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rafta Rafta \u2013 Royal National Theatre|url=http://www.japjitkaur.com/projects/rafta-rafta-royal-national-theatre/|website=Japjit Kaur}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Patel|first1=Chandrika|title=The Taste of British South Asian Theatres: Aesthetics and Production|date=2015|publisher=Lulu Press|isbn=9781483433417|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EBafCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT103&lpg=PT103&dq=harish+patel+%2B+theatre&source=bl&ots=5zIsLsmuXA&sig=GYm51BVnINQnZhN2ect9skhcujQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzg6PR5t7KAhVKnRoKHdmRAlsQ6AEIUzAI#v=onepage&q=harish%20patel%20%2B%20theatre&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"The Guardian 1 May 2007\">{{cite web|title=Wanted: multicultural audiences for mainstream theatre|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/theatreblog/2007/may/01/wantedmulticulturalaudiences|website=The Guardian|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nHis credits include ''[[The Buddha of Suburbia (TV serial)|The Buddha of Suburbia]]'', ''[[China Gate (1998 film)|China Gate]]'', ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr India]]'' and ''[[Run Fatboy Run]]''.<ref name=\"The Asian Today 5 Sep 2007\">{{cite web|title=\u2018I couldn\u2019t say no to David\u2019 \u2013 Harish Patel|url=http://www.theasiantoday.com/index.php/2007/09/05/i-couldnt-say-no-to-david-harish-patel/|publisher=The Asian Today}}</ref> In 2009 he appeared in ''[[Coronation Street]]'' playing the role of Umed, [[Dev Alahan]]'s uncle. Patel also appeared in ''[[Mr Stink (film)|Mr Stink]]'', ''[[Gangsta Granny (film)|Gangsta Granny]]'', ''[[The Boy in the Dress (film)|The Boy in the Dress]]'' and ''[[Billionaire Boy (film)|Billionaire Boy]]'', the television film adaptations of children's books by [[David Walliams]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Billionaire Boy|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/dw488j/billionaire-boy|website=Radio Times|publisher=Radio Times}}</ref> He plays shopkeeper Raj in all the films, although they are set in different places.\n\nHis acting career has taken him all over India, and he has performed in the United Kingdom and abroad, in the United States and [[Dubai]] among other countries. Patel is a life member of the [[Federation of Western India Cine Employees|Cine & TV Artists Association of India]].\n\nHe is well known for his catchphrase: ''gayee bhains paanee mein'' (the buffalo entered the water), in the movie, ''Mr. India''.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n\n===Television===\n* ''[[Four Weddings and a Funeral (miniseries)|Four Weddings and a Funeral]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Billionaire Boy (film)|Billionaire Boy]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Driver (TV series)|The Driver]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[The Boy in the Dress (film)|The Boy in the Dress]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Mapp and Lucia (BBC TV series)|Mapp and Lucia]]'' (2014)\n*\n\n* ''[[Gangsta Granny (film)|Gangsta Granny]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Mr Stink (film)|Mr Stink]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Baa Bahoo Aur Baby]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Coronation Street]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[The No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency (TV series)|The No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency]]'' (2008)\n* ''Gopaljee'' (1996)\n* ''[[The Buddha of Suburbia (TV serial)|The Buddha of Suburbia]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Wagle Ki Duniya]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Malgudi Days (TV series)|Malgudi Days]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Yatra (1986 TV series)|Yatra]]'' (1986)\n\n===Films===\n* ''Lies We Tell'' (2016)\n* ''[[Jadoo (UK film)|Jadoo]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Keith Lemon: The Film]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[All in Good Time (film)|All in Good Time]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Today's Special (film)|Today's Special]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Kisse Pyaar Karoon]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Run Fatboy Run]]'' (2007)\n* ''Chicken Tikka Masala'' (2005)\n* ''[[Pyaar Mein Twist]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Thoda Tum Badlo Thoda Hum]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Calcutta Mail]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Love at Times Square]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Ek Hindustani]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Kuch Tum Kaho Kuch Hum Kahein]]'' (2002)\n* ''Bokshu, the Myth'' (2002)<ref>{{cite web|last=Young|first=Deborah|title=Bokshu, The Myth|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/markets-festivals/bokshu-the-myth-1200515561/|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=18 December 2017|date=13 June 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Warrier|first=Shobha|title=Why can't an Indian make a film in English?|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2002/may/22sen.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=18 December 2017|date=22 May 2002}}</ref>\n* ''[[Pyaar Ishq Aur Mohabbat]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Zubeidaa]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Dhaai Akshar Prem Ke]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Krodh (film)|Krodh]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Jab Pyaar Kisise Hota Hai]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Gunda (1998 film)|Gunda]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Purani Kabar]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Gupt: The Hidden Truth]]''(1997)\n* ''[[Loha (1997 film)|Loha]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[My Son the Fanatic (film)|My Son the Fanatic]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Kama Sutra: A Tale of Love]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Ghatak: Lethal]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Mohra]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Andaz Apna Apna]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Aankhen (1993 film)|Aankhen]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Police Public]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Maine Pyaar Kiya]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr India]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Mandi (film)|Mandi]]'' (1983)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0665370}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patel, Harish}}\n[[Category:Male film actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Male television actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:British people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n\n\n{{theat-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zeroegorki", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harish_Patel"}
